      level: 5,
      summary: 'Wound closure science integrates wound healing biology with infection control principles. Evidence supports flexible timing for primary closure with adequate preparation. Modern materials and techniques optimize outcomes. Decision frameworks guide appropriate technique selection.',
      explanation: `## Wound Healing Biology

### Phases and Closure
- Inflammatory: 1-4 days
- Proliferative: 4-21 days
- Remodeling: 21 days - 1 year
- Closure approximates edges during proliferative phase

### Tension and Healing
- Excessive tension causes necrosis
- Deep closure reduces surface tension
- Relaxed skin tension lines guide incisions
- Undermining may reduce tension

## Evidence Base

### Closure Timing
- Prospective studies suggest flexibility
- Risk factors more important than time:
  - Contamination
  - Tissue devitalization
  - Host factors (diabetes, immunocompromise)

### Wound Preparation
- Irrigation most important factor
- Debridement as needed
- Edge freshening for delayed wounds
- Hair removal: clipping not shaving

## Advanced Materials

### Absorbable Sutures
| Material | Absorption | Strength Retention |
|----------|------------|-------------------|
| Vicryl | 56-70 days | 50% at 3 weeks |
| Monocryl | 91-119 days | 50% at 1 week |
| PDS | 180+ days | 50% at 4 weeks |

### Tissue Adhesives
- 2-octyl cyanoacrylate (Dermabond)
- n-butyl-2-cyanoacrylate
- Polymerizes on contact with tissue
- Antimicrobial properties

## Special Situations

### Flaps and Avulsions
- Assess viability
- Debride if needed
- Gentle handling
- Avoid tension

### Stellate Lacerations
- Complex geometry
- May need revision
- Key sutures first
- Accept some irregularity

## Wilderness Applications
- Limited equipment reality
- Training appropriate techniques
- When to close vs evacuate
- Telemedicine guidance`,
